05733nam a22008655i 9780813542539DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20042004nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135425397 a10.36019/97808135425392doi  a(DE-B1597)529776  a(OCoLC)804665137  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aGE220b.N48 2004eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a363.722200aNew Perspectives on Environmental Justice :bGender, Sexuality, and Activism /cRachel Stein. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- t1 Toward a Queer Ecofeminism -- t2 Women, Sexuality, and Environmental Justice in American History -- t3 Feminist Theory and Environmental Justice -- t4 Witness to Truth: Black Women Heeding the Call for Environmental Justice -- t5 The Role of Gender, Race/Ethnicity, and Class in Activists' Perceptions of Environmental Justice -- t6 Sexual Politics and Environmental Justice: Lesbian Separatists in Rural Oregon -- t7 Toxic Bodies? ACT UP's Disruption of the Heteronormative Landscape of the Nation -- t8 Producing "Roundup Ready®" Communities? Human Genome Research and Environmental Justice Policy -- t9 Public Eyes: Investigating the Causes of Breast Cancer -- t10 Gender, Asthma Politics, and Urban Environmental Justice Activism -- t11 No Remedy for the Inuit: Accountability for Environmental Harms under U.S. and International Law -- t12 Bodily Invasions: Gene Trading and Organ Theft in Octavia Butler and Nalo Hopkinson's Speculative Fiction -- t13 Home Everywhere and the Injured Body of the World: The Subversive Humor of Blue Vinyl -- t14 "Lo que quiero es tierra": Longing and Belonging in Cherríe Moraga's Ecological Vision -- t15 Detecting Toxic Environments: Gay Mystery as Environmental Justice -- t16 "The Power is Yours, Planeteers!" Race, Gender, and Sexuality in Children's Environmental Popular Culture -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWomen make up the vast majority of activists and organizers of grassroots movements fighting against environmental ills that threaten poor and people of color communities. New Perspectives on Environmental Justice is the first collection of essays that pays tribute to the enormous contributions women have made in these endeavors. The writers offer varied examples of environmental justice issues such as children's environmental health campaigns, cancer research, AIDS/HIV activism, the Environmental Genome Project, and popular culture, among many others. Each one focuses on gender and sexuality as crucial factors in women's or gay men's activism and applies environmental justice principles to related struggles for sexual justice. The contributors represent a wide variety of activist and scholarly perspectives including law, environmental studies, sociology, political science, history, medical anthropology, American studies, English, African and African American studies, women's studies, and gay and lesbian studies, offering multiple vantage points on gender, sexuality, and activism. Feminist/womanist impulses shape and sustain environmental justice movements around the world, making an understanding of gender roles and differences crucial for the success of these efforts.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aEnvironmental justice. 0aWomen environmentalists. 0aWomenxPolitical activity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBerila, Beth1 aChiro, Giovanna Di1 aGaard, Greta1 aHogan, Katie1 aKaalund, Valerie1 aLaDuke, Winona1 aLucas, Anne1 aNewman, Marcy Knopf1 aPlevin, Arlene